  "lesson_number": 27,
  "title": "Lesson 27",
  "topic": "Masculine nouns ending in -u/-ū",
  "grammar": {
    "explanations": [
      "Masculine nouns ending in -u are declined according to the pattern of 'garu' (teacher). The nominative, vocative, and accusative singular all take the base form 'garu', while the accusative singular adds -ṃ. The instrumental and ablative singular take -nā. The dative and genitive singular have two forms: -no and -ssa. The locative singular takes -mhi or -smiṃ. In the plural, the nominative, vocative, and accusative take -ū or -avo. The instrumental and ablative plural take -ūhi (or -ūbhi). The dative and genitive plural take -ūnaṃ. The locative plural takes -ūsu.",
      "Masculine nouns ending in -ū are declined similarly to the -u declension. Using 'vidū' (wise man) as a model, the nominative, vocative, and accusative singular all take the base form 'vidū', while the accusative singular adds -ṃ (viduṃ). The plural nominative, vocative, and accusative take -ū or -uno. The remaining cases follow the same pattern as the garu declension."
    ],
    "tables": [
      {
        "title": "Declension of garu (teacher) - masculine noun ending in -u",
        "rows": [
          ["Case", "Singular", "Plural"],
          ["Nom.", "garu", "garū, garavo"],
